{
    "level": "A2–B1",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn to separate <strong>Present Perfect</strong> from <strong>Past Simple</strong> by looking at the connection to the present moment.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "RESULT NOW",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "<strong>Present Perfect</strong> shows a result now, life experience, or a period up to the present:",
            "example": "I have lost my keys."
        },
        {
            "label": "FINISHED PAST",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "<strong>Past Simple</strong> shows a finished action at a definite past time:",
            "example": "I lost my keys yesterday."
        },
        {
            "label": "TIME WORDS",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "Words like <strong>yesterday, last year, ago</strong> point to Past Simple, while <strong>ever, never, already, yet, just</strong> often go with Present Perfect.",
            "example": "Have you ever been there? / I went there last year."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Quick comparison",
    "intro": "Look at the difference in meaning and time markers.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Present Perfect",
            "title": "have / has + V3",
            "subtitle": "I have finished. / She has already left."
        },
        {
            "label": "Past Simple",
            "title": "V2 / did",
            "subtitle": "I finished yesterday. / Did she leave early?"
        },
        {
            "label": "Unfinished period",
            "title": "today / this week / in my life",
            "subtitle": "often Present Perfect"
        },
        {
            "label": "Finished time",
            "title": "yesterday / in 2019 / last night / ago",
            "subtitle": "normally Past Simple"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. When to use each form",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Present Perfect: result and experience",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "This form connects a past action with a <strong>result now</strong> or with life experience.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I have lost my keys, so I cannot open the door.",
                    "ua": "I have lost my keys, so I cannot open the door."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She has visited Rome three times.",
                    "ua": "She has visited Rome three times."
                },
                {
                    "en": "We have lived here for five years.",
                    "ua": "We have lived here for five years."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Past Simple: a finished moment in the past",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "When the time is <strong>finished and named</strong>, you need Past Simple.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I lost my keys yesterday.",
                    "ua": "I lost my keys yesterday."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She visited Rome in 2022.",
                    "ua": "She visited Rome in 2022."
                },
                {
                    "en": "We lived there when I was a child.",
                    "ua": "We lived there when I was a child."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Unfinished time vs finished time",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "<strong>Today / this week / this year</strong> may still be unfinished, while <strong>yesterday / last week</strong> is finished.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I have seen Anna twice this week.",
                    "ua": "I have seen Anna twice this week."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I saw Anna twice last week.",
                    "ua": "I saw Anna twice last week."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Have you eaten today?",
                    "ua": "Have you eaten today?"
                }
            ],
            "note": "Ask yourself: is this time period still open, or is it already finished?"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Present Perfect with yesterday.",
            "wrong": "I have seen him yesterday.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I saw him yesterday.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Past Simple for life experience.",
            "wrong": "Did you ever visit London?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Have you ever visited London?</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Past Simple with for / since when the situation continues now.",
            "wrong": "We lived here for five years. <span class=\"text-slate-500\">(and still live here)</span>",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">We have lived here for five years.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "<strong>Present Perfect</strong> = present connection, result now, experience, period up to now.",
        "<strong>Past Simple</strong> = finished time or finished period in the past.",
        "<strong>Yesterday, last, ago, in 2020</strong> almost always lead to Past Simple.",
        "<strong>Ever, never, already, yet, just, for, since</strong> often appear with Present Perfect.",
        "Key question: is the time still connected to now, or is it completely finished?"
    ]
}

